## Dependencies
npm install @excalidraw/excalidraw --workspace packages/springstack

The @excalidraw/excalidraw package provides a full React component for rendering Excalidraw scenes. It is a large dependency (~2MB) but is the official way to render .excalidraw files.

Alternative lightweight approach: use @excalidraw/utils exportToSvg() to render to static SVG without the full editor. This is significantly lighter. Decide based on bundle size concerns.

## File: packages/springstack/src/fileTypes/ExcalidrawContent.tsx

Component:
1. useState for parsed Excalidraw scene data (elements, appState, files)
2. useEffect to fetch(node.data.url).then(r => r.json()) on mount
3. Render Excalidraw component in view-only mode:
   <Excalidraw
     initialData={{ elements, appState: { ...appState, viewModeEnabled: true } }}
     viewModeEnabled={true}
     zenModeEnabled={true}
     UIOptions={{ canvasActions: { export: false, saveAsImage: false } }}
   />
4. Container with fixed height (e.g., h-96) for the canvas

## Lightweight Alternative (if bundle size is a concern)
import { exportToSvg } from '@excalidraw/utils';
const svg = await exportToSvg({ elements, appState, files });
// Render SVG directly - much lighter, no interactive canvas

